article.description: Alonzo Mourning was his dominant old self in his second game since having a kidney transplant 11 months ago, making back-to-back layups in the second overtime to lead the New Jersey Nets to a 111-106 victory over the Chicago Bulls.

related.description: Uncertain of how long he'll be able to play after having a kidney transplant, Alonzo Mourning has asked the New Jersey Nets about a contract buyout so he could go to a team with a better chance of winning.
related.linkText: 'Zo asks Nets for buyout to play for winner
related.title: Sides can't agree to financial terms
related.headline: Sides can't agree to financial terms

article.headline: New Jersey needs double overtime to beat Chicago
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- As dominant as Alonzo Mourning was in his second game since having a kidney transplant, he promises to be better. Mourning made back-to-back shots in the second overtime and the New Jersey Nets held on to beat the Chicago Bulls 111-106 on Friday night. Mourning played 26 minutes, finishing with 17 points on 5-of-5 shooting, six blocks and five rebounds. "I feel fine," said Mourning, who had a kidney transplant last Dec. 19. "I know what I'm capable of doing and I've still got a ton of room for improvement. I expect more from myself. I've just got to continue to improve and progress, and the only way I'm going to do that is to continue to play." Richard Jefferson just missed a triple-double, finishing with 26 points, a career-high 21 rebounds and nine assists -- including dishes to Mourning on the final two shots. The Nets won despite blowing a 27-point lead. Kirk Hinrich scored 17 of his career-high 34 points in the third quarter, leading the Bulls on a furious rally in their season opener. Rookie Luol Deng had a double-double in his first NBA game, finishing with 18 points and 10 rebounds. But the Bulls fell short, going 3-of-16 in overtime. "It was tough," said Hinrich, who was cramping up in overtime. "Especially when you get down by so much, you spend so much energy to get back in the game." Mourning knows a little about that. The All-Star center retired last November because of complications from focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, a kidney disease that was first diagnosed in 2000. But after the transplant, he decided to play again. Mourning knows his time is limited, though, and he said before the game that he's asked the Nets for a buyout so he could go to a team with a better chance of winning. The sides are millions apart, but Mourning promised it won't affect his play. "When I step out on the court, I play each minute like it's my last," he said before the game. "Because there's a possibility it is." The Nets led by 24 almost four minutes into the third quarter, but the Bulls outscored them 59-39 to force overtime. Jefferson almost won the game in regulation, making what he thought was a 3-pointer with four seconds left. After Hinrich missed a running 3, the Nets began running off the court, thinking they'd won. But replays showed the tip of Jefferson's right shoe was clearly on the line, and the game was headed for overtime. Nets coach Lawrence Frank was already off the floor, and he looked around incredulously when an assistant waved him back. "I thought it was a 3," Jefferson said. "I was ready to run off the court, but 'Zo said, 'Richard, your foot was on the line.'" Mourning had a chance to win it in the first overtime, going to the line when Othella Harrington fouled him with 1:14 to play. But after making 7-of-8 free throws in regulation, he missed both attempts. He made amends in the second OT, though. Jefferson fed him inside for a layup with 1:24 left that gave the Nets a 105-103 lead. About 30 seconds later, they ran the same play again, putting the Bulls away. "As well as we played in the first half, that's how bad we played in the second," Jefferson said. "It's going to take some time, we understand that. It's a new system. The more comfortable guys get, the more consistent they're going to be." Mourning agreed. "When you're a team that's just been assembled ... you're going to run into situations where you're not familiar with each other," he said. "The only way you're going to grow is through communication and time on the court together. This was a growth situation." For the Bulls, too, even if the outcome wasn't as good. Chicago was horrid in the first half, getting outscored 35-6 as the Bulls fell behind 41-15. They still trailed by 24 early in the third when Hinrich, selected as a captain in only his second season, got hot. He scored 17 points in the quarter, including 12 during a 20-4 five-minute spurt that pulled Chicago within 67-59. Hinrich was everywhere, hitting layups, banking a 3 off the glass as the shot clock expired, even forcing a turnover by taking a hard charge. Jefferson finally stopped the run with a driving layup, but Hinrich hit another 3 with 21 seconds left in the quarter, cutting New Jersey's lead to 73-66 going into the fourth. Then Deng, the seventh pick in the draft after just one year at Duke, took over. He scored nine straight points, drilling a 3-pointer to tie the game and tipping in an airball to give the Bulls a 79-77 lead. The Chicago bench jumped to its feet as the ball went in and fans -- who'd booed the Bulls loudly in the first half -- roared. "We didn't get the 'W,'" Deng said. "So I don't know what kind of a statement we made."

Game notes
Hinrich's previous career high was 29, against Atlanta on April 9. ... The Nets have won four straight against the Bulls. ... The Bulls have won just one home opener since their dynasty days, beating New Orleans two years ago.
